:"1286–1312","1330":"1330","1374":"1374","1286":"1286","1340":"1340","1395":"1395","1380":"1380","Abt 1340":"circa 1340","Abt 1395":"circa 1395","1312":"1312","1345":"1345","1310":"1310","1364":"1364","1397":"1397","about 1310":"circa 1310","1319":"1319","1406":"1406","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Schotland","Cumbernauld, , Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Biggar, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Biggar, Lanarkshire, Schotland","Haddington, East Lothian, Scotland":"Haddington, Haddingtonshire, Schotland","Biggar, South Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Biggar, South Lanarkshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1310–Abt 1395":"about 1310–about 1395","1310–1395":"1310–1395","1319–1380":"1319–1380","1330–1406":"1330–1406","1345–1397":"1345–1397","1286–1340":"1286–1340","1286–1312":"1286–1312","1330":"1330","1374":"1374","1286":"1286","1340":"1340","1395":"1395","1380":"1380","Abt 1340":"about 1340","Abt 1395":"about 1395","1312":"1312","1345":"1345","1310":"1310","1364":"1364","1397":"1397","about 1310":"about 1310","1319":"1319","1406":"1406","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","Cumbernauld, , Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Biggar, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Biggar, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Haddington, East Lothian, Scotland":"Haddington, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Biggar, South Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Biggar, South Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fleming","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: ethnic name for someone from Flanders, from Middle English <i>fleming</i>. The word reflects a Norman French form of Old French <i>flamanc</i> ‘Fleming’, from the stem <i>flam-</i> + the ancient Germanic suffix <i>-ing</i>. In the Middle Ages there was considerable commercial intercourse between England and the Netherlands, particularly in the wool trade, and many Flemish weavers and dyers settled in England. This surname is also common in south and east Scotland and in Ireland, where it is sometimes found in the Gaelicized form <b>Pléamonn</b>.","German: variant of   Flemming  , cognate with 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Flemings","meanings":["English: plural form of   Fleming  .","Americanized form of Flemish <b>Vleminckx</b>: patronymic from <b>Vleminck</b>, an ethnic name for someone from Flanders, Middle Dutch <i>vleminc</i>."]},{"name":"Flanders","meanings":["English: ethnic name from Middle English <i>Fla(u)ndres</i> ‘Flanders’, denoting someone from Flanders, a historical region covering parts of modern-day Belgium, France, and the Netherlands. Compare   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Fleeman","meanings":["English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flemming","meanings":["German: ethnic name for someone from Flanders, Middle High German <i>vlaeminc</i>. People from Flanders spread throughout Germany, as well as England, in the Middle Ages as clothmakers and dyers.","English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flamenco","meanings":["Spanish: ethnic name from <i>flamenco</i> ‘Fleming, Flemish person’ (see   Fleming  )."]}]},{"name":"Malcolm","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the medieval Gaelic name <i>Mael Coluim</i> ‘devotee of St Columba’. Columba was a 6th-century monk of Irish origin who played a leading part in the conversion to Christianity of Scotland and northern England;  see also  Callum   and   Colm .  He has always been one of the most popular saints in Scotland, but in the Middle Ages it was felt to be presumptuous to give the names of saints directly to children; instead their blessing was invoked by prefixing the name with <i>mael</i> ‘devotee of’ or <i>gille</i> ‘servant of’. Since the 1930s the given name has been used widely in the English-speaking world, not just by those with Scottish connections."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Malcolm Fleming was born about 1310, in Biggar, Lanarkshire, Scotland, his father, Sir Patrick Fleming, was 25 and his mother, Joanna Fraser, was 26. He married Christina Keith in 1330, in Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. In 1374, at the age of 65, his occupation is listed as sheriff of edinburgh. He died about 1395, in his hometown, at the age of 87."},"et":{"about 1310–Abt 1395":"umbes 1310–umbes 1395","1310–1395":"1310–1395","1319–1380":"1319–1380","1330–1406":"1330–1406","1345–1397":"1345–1397","1286–1340":"1286–1340","1286–1312":"1286–1312","1330":"1330","1374":"1374","1286":"1286","1340":"1340","1395":"1395","1380":"1380","Abt 1340":"umbes 1340","Abt 1395":"umbes 1395","1312":"1312","1345":"1345","1310":"1310","1364":"1364","1397":"1397","about 1310":"umbes 1310","1319":"1319","1406":"1406","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","Cumbernauld, , Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Biggar, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Biggar, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Haddington, East Lothian, Scotland":"Haddington, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Biggar, South Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Biggar, South Lanarkshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1310–Abt 1395":"noin 1310–noin 1395","1310–1395":"1310–1395","1319–1380":"1319–1380","1330–1406":"1330–1406","1345–1397":"1345–1397","1286–1340":"1286–1340","1286–1312":"1286–1312","1330":"1330","1374":"1374","1286":"1286","1340":"1340","1395":"1395","1380":"1380","Abt 1340":"noin 1340","Abt 1395":"noin 1395","1312":"1312","1345":"1345","1310":"1310","1364":"1364","1397":"1397","about 1310":"noin 1310","1319":"1319","1406":"1406","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","Cumbernauld, , Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Biggar, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Biggar, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Haddington, East Lothian, Scotland":"Haddington, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Biggar, South Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Bigg